## Inflation regressions {.tabset}

This section tests whether the default effects go through inflation. The approach is as follows:

1. Do a predictive regression of inflation onto debt growth and CDS, and possibly other controls. These variables are considered default risk proxies (column 1).
$$
  \frac{1}{h}\sum_{i=1}^h\pi_{t+i} = a_h + b_h^{(CDS)} CDS_t +b_h D_t+ b_h^{(X)'} X_t +\varepsilon_{t+h}
$$

2. Regress the ILSBEI spread onto the fitted values of the regression and the controls (column 2). 

3. Test whether the individual CDS and Debt growth add anything to the fit. We regress the ILSBEI residual from the previous regression onto CDS, Debt growth, and controls (column 4).


Column 3 presents the regression of ILSBEI with individual default proxies and controls instead of the fitted values from the first stage. Standard errors are Newey-West but do not adjust for the different steps in the estimation. There should be a way to do a F-test directly but I didn't know how to do that with Newey-West. 


